\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose a box contains 3 balls : 1 red, 1 green, and 1 blue
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider an experiment that consists of taking 1 ball from the box and then
 replacing it in the box and drawing a second ball from the box.
 List all possible outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider an experiment that consists of taking 1 ball from the box and then
 drawing a second ball from the box without replacing the first.
 List all possible outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are mutually exclusive events for which 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A)=.3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P(B)=.5$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 occurs but 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 does not? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the probability that neither 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 occurs? 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Forty percent of college students from a certain college are members of
 neither an academic club nor a greek organization.
 Fifty percent are members of academic clubs while thirty percent are members
 of a greek organization.
 Suppose a student is chosen at random, what is the probability that this
 students is a member
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
of an academic club or a greek organization?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
of an academic club and a greek organization?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
In City, 60% of the households subscribe to newspaper A, 50% to newspaper
 B, 40% to newspaper C, 30% to A and B, 20% to B and C, and 10% to A and
 C, but none subscribe to all three.
 (Hint: Draw a Venn diagram)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What percentage subscribe to exactly one newspaper?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What percentage subscribe to at most one newspaper?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
There are 52 cards in a standard deck of playing cards.
 The 
\emph on
poker hand 
\emph default
is consists of five cards.
 There are 4 
\emph on
suits
\emph default
: heats, spades, diamonds, and clubs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\heartsuit\spadesuit\diamondsuit\clubsuit\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The suit's diamonds and clubs are red while clubs and spades are black.
 In each suit there are 13 
\emph on
ranks
\emph default
: The Ace card, the numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $2,3\dots,10$
\end_inset

, the face cards, Jack, Queen and King.
 Find the probability of randomly drawing the following poker hands.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
All red cards?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Exactly two 10's and exactly three aces?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
all face cards or no face cards?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Find the probability of randomly drawing the following poker hands.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\emph on
one pair, 
\emph default
which consists of two cards of the same rank and three other distinct ranks.
 (e.g.
 22Q59)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\emph on
two pair
\emph default
, which constists of two cards of the same rank, two cards of another rank,
 and another card of yet another rank.
 (e.g.
 JJ779)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\emph on
three of a kind
\emph default
, which consists of a three cards of the same rank, and two others of distinct
 rank.
 (e.g.
 4449K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\emph on
flush
\emph default
, which consists of all five cards of the same suit.
 (e.g.
 HHHH, SSSS, DDDD, or CCCC)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\emph on
full house
\emph default
, which consists of a two pair and a three of a kind.
 (e.g.
 88844) (Hint: Note that 88844 is a different hand than a 44488)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose a standard deck of cards is modifed with the additional rank of
 
\emph on
Super King
\emph default
 and the additional suit of 
\emph on
Swords
\emph default
 so now each card has one of 14 ranks and one of 5 suits.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If a card is selected at random, what is the probability that it's the 
\emph on
Super King of Swords
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What's the probability of getting a six card hand with exactly three pairs
 (two cards of one rank and two cards of another rank and two cards of yet
 another rank, e.g.
 7,7,2,2,J,J) ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What's the probability of getting a six card hand which constists of three
 cards of the same rank, two cards of another rank, and another card of
 yet another rank.
 (e.g.
 3,3,3,A,A,7)? 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A pair of fair dice is rolled.
 What is the probability that the first die lands on a strictly higher value
 than the second die.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There are 8 students in a class.
 What is the probability that at least two students share a common birthday
 month? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Nine balls are randomly withdrawn from an urn that contains 10 blue, 12
 red, and 15 green balls.
 What is the probability that
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
2 blue, 5 red, and 2 green balls are withdrawn
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
at least 2 blue balls are withdrawn.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 4 valedictorians (from different high schools) were all accepted
 to the 8 Ivy League universities.
 What is the probability that they each choose to go to a different Ivy
 League university? 
\end_layout

