\begin_layout Chapter
Conditional Probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Two dice are rolled.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ \mbox{sum of two dice equals 3}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left\{ \mbox{sum of two dice equals 7 }\right\} $
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\left\{ \mbox{at least one of the dice shows a 1}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left(A\mid C\right)?$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left(B\mid C\right)$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Are 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 indepedent? What about 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose you roll a two standard, fair, 6-sided dice.
 What is the probability that the sum is at least 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

 given that you rolled at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that Annabelle and Bobby each draw 13 cards from a standard deck
 of 52.
 Given that Sarah has exactly two aces, what is the probability that Bobby
 has exactly one ace?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that 60% of UConn students will be exposed to the flu.
 If you are exposed and didn't get the flu shot, then the probability that
 you will get the flu (
\emph on
after being exposed
\emph default
) is 80%, but if you did get the flu shot, the probability that you will
 get the flu (
\emph on
after being exposed
\emph default
) is only 15%.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the probability that a person who got the flu shot will get the
 flu ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the probability that a person who did not get the flu shot will
 get the flu?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Color blindness is a sex-linked condition, and 5% of men and 0.25% of women
 are color blind.
 The population of the United States is 51% female.
 What is the probability that a color-blind American is a man?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that two factories supply light bulbs to the market.
 Factory X’s bulbs work for over 5000 hours in 99% of cases, whereas factory
 Y’s bulbs work for over 5000 hours in 95% of cases.
 It is known that factory X supplies 60% of the total bulbs available.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the chance that a purchased bulb will work for longer than 5000
 hours? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given that a lightbulb works for more than 5000 hours, what is the probability
 that it came from factory 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given that a lightbulb work does not work for more than 5000 hours, what
 is the probability that it came from factory 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A factory production line is manufacturing bolts using three machines, A,
 B and C.
 Of the total output, machine A is responsible for 25%, machine B for 35%
 and machine C for the rest.
 It is known from previous experience with the machines that 5% of the output
 from machine A is defective, 4% from machine B and 2% from machine C.
 A bolt is chosen at random from the production line and found to be defective.
 What is the probability that it came from Machine 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A multiple choice exam has 4 choices for each question.
 A student has studied enough so that the probability they will know the
 answer to a question is 0.5, the probability that they will be able to eliminate
 one choice is 0.25, otherwise all 4 choices seem equally plausible.
 If they know the answer they will get the question right.
 If not they have to guess from the 3 or 4 choices.
 As the teacher you want the test to measure what the student knows.
 If the student answers a question correctly what's the probability they
 knew the answer?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A blood test indicates the presence of a particular disease 95% of the time
 when the disease is actually present.
 The same test indicates the presence of the disease 0.5% of the time when
 the disease is not actually present.
 One percent of the population actually has the disease.
 Calculate the probability that a person actually has the disease given
 that the test indicates the presence of the disease.
\end_layout

